{"id":"mai-fczb","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 3: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian — Root Cause \u0026 Design","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 3: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian — Research Findings\n\n## 1. Instructor Framing Assessment\n\nThe ticket framing is **mostly accurate** but contains one subtle bias: it frames the problem as potentially being about Obsidian's save behavior (atomic saves, temp files, etc.). While Obsidian's save behavior matters for the daemon's fsnotify handling (and the codebase already addresses this with debouncing), **the core duplication bug has nothing to do with HOW Obsidian saves files**. The bug is in the CRDT merge logic itself.\n\nThe framing's emphasis on \"should we even use CRDTs?\" is a valid question worth investigating, but the actual bug is a simpler algorithmic error that CRDTs would work fine for if implemented correctly.\n\n## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)\n\nAfter reading every relevant source file completely, I formed three hypotheses:\n\n**H1 (CONFIRMED — Root Cause): Stale/wrong 3-way merge base causes both sides to \"insert\" the full document**\n\nThe `mergeViaCRDT` function (docs.go:530-600) does a 3-way merge where:\n1. It creates a \"base\" YDoc from `creationBody` (the note's original body at creation time)\n2. It creates a \"note peer\" from the base and applies diff(base → noteContent)\n3. It creates a \"file peer\" from the base and applies diff(base → fileContent)\n4. It merges them\n\nThe problem: as the document evolves through many edits, the `creationBody` drifts increasingly far from both `noteContent` and `fileContent`. When you diff a very old base against the current content, the diff engine sees *nearly the entire document* as new insertions. When two peers both \"insert\" nearly identical large blocks of text at similar positions, the CRDT correctly preserves both insertions — resulting in massive duplication.\n\nThis is the **exact same problem** described in a StackOverflow answer about Yjs: \"Yjs interprets that as deleting all existing text and inserting all new text; if two users do so concurrently, they both insert the complete new text, duplicating it.\"\n\n**H2 (CONFIRMED — Contributing factor): `lastSyncBody()` returns empty string**\n\nThe function `lastSyncBody()` at docs.go:517 has a TODO and returns \"\". It was designed to track the last-synced body but was never implemented. The code falls back to `creationBody` which gets staler with every edit.\n\n**H3 (INVESTIGATED — Not the primary cause): Obsidian's save behavior**\n\nObsidian is an Electron app that uses Node.js `fs` APIs. On macOS, it uses `vault.adapter.write()` which does a full-file write (not an atomic rename-dance like vim). The daemon already handles this correctly with a 500ms debounce window. The existing test `TestDaemon_AtomicSaveDoesNotTombstone` proves this works. Obsidian's full-file-write behavior is **not** the cause of the duplication bug.\n\n## 3. Research Path — Every Avenue Explored\n\n### 3.1 Source Code Trace: File Save → Garbled Output\n\nFull path traced:\n```\nObsidian saves file → fsnotify.Write event\n  → daemon.go event loop, debounce map, 200ms quiet\n  → syncFile() → getOrCreateEngine() → notes.SyncDocs()\n    → SyncDocs: disk file hash ≠ note hash → mergeViaCRDT()\n      → mergeViaCRDT: loads YDoc from state\n        → creates base from creationBody\n        → diffs base→noteContent, applies ops to notePeer\n        → diffs base→fileContent, applies ops to filePeer\n        → merges filePeer state into notePeer\n        → BUG: when base is stale, both diffs are huge → CRDT preserves both → duplication\n```\n\n### 3.2 CRDT Engine Analysis\n\nThe yrs WASM layer itself is correct. The `pkg/crdt/crdt.go` implementation correctly:\n- Uses unique client IDs per peer (randomClientID())\n- Supports Save/Load/Apply for full-state merge\n- Has proper Insert/Delete operations\n\nThe `pkg/crdt/diff.go` correctly computes minimal edit sequences using Myers diff. The `ApplyOps` function correctly applies them.\n\nThe bug is NOT in the CRDT engine. It's in **how the merge orchestration code uses it**.\n\n### 3.3 The Stale Base Problem — Detailed\n\nConsider a concrete scenario:\n\n1. Note created with body: \"Hello World\" (this is `creationBody`)\n2. User edits in Obsidian over 20 saves → body becomes \"Hello World\\n\\nThis is a long document with many paragraphs about architecture...\"\n3. An agent updates the note body (adds a tag or fixes a typo)\n4. On next SyncDocs, hashes differ, mergeViaCRDT is called with:\n   - `creationBody` = \"Hello World\"  (10 chars)\n   - `noteContent` = \"Hello World\\n\\nThis is a long document...\" (2700 words)\n   - `fileContent` = \"Hello World\\n\\nThis is a long document...\" (2700 words, slight diff)\n\n5. Diff(\"Hello World\", noteContent) → one giant Insert op for ~2700 words\n6. Diff(\"Hello World\", fileContent) → one giant Insert op for ~2700 words (almost identical)\n7. Both peers insert ~2700 words at the same position\n8. CRDT merge: preserves BOTH insertions → 5400+ words of mostly duplicated text\n\nThis perfectly matches the observed symptom: \"line fragments get duplicated 40+ times\" and \"document goes from ~2700 words to 15,778 characters\".\n\n### 3.4 Why the Existing CRDT Tests Don't Catch This\n\nThe existing tests in `crdt_test.go` test concurrent edits where both peers start from the same loaded state. They test:\n- Two peers editing different parts (works perfectly)\n- Two peers inserting at the same position (both inserts preserved — correct CRDT behavior)\n\nBut none test the scenario where two peers start from a BASE that's radically different from the actual content, and both apply near-identical large diffs. The merge *is* correct from the CRDT's perspective — it's just not what we want.\n\n### 3.5 Obsidian File Save Behavior\n\nBased on research:\n- Obsidian is an Electron app using Node.js\n- It saves files via its `vault.adapter.write()` API\n- On desktop, this maps to `fs.writeFile()` — a full file write, not an atomic rename\n- Obsidian auto-saves frequently (default: 2 seconds after stop typing, configurable)\n- On macOS, this triggers a `fsnotify.Write` event (not Remove+Create)\n- The daemon correctly handles this with debouncing\n\n### 3.6 How Other Tools Handle This\n\n- **Logseq**: Uses file-level conflict detection. Shows \"File modified on disk\" warning. Relies on git for merge resolution. No CRDT layer for file-to-note sync.\n- **Dendron**: Stores notes as plain markdown. Uses VS Code's built-in file watching. No CRDT — relies on git history and manual conflict resolution.\n- **Syncthing**: File-level sync with `.sync-conflict` files for conflicts. No line-level merge.\n- **Obsidian Sync**: Proprietary, but reportedly uses CRDT internally for collaborative editing. However, this is for live collaboration, not file-to-note sync.\n- **Relay (Obsidian plugin)**: Uses y-crdt for live collaboration between Obsidian clients. Operates at the editor level (ProseMirror-like binding), not at the file-to-note level.\n\nKey insight: **No existing tool tries to do what maitake does** — bidirectional sync between a git-backed note store and an external editor's file. Most either:\n1. Own the file exclusively (Obsidian Sync, Logseq)\n2. Use git directly (Dendron)\n3. Use CRDTs for live editor collaboration (Relay, y-prosemirror)\n\n## 4. Dead Ends and Why\n\n### 4.1 Obsidian Atomic Saves — Not the Issue\nI initially investigated whether Obsidian uses atomic saves (write temp + rename) that might confuse fsnotify. It doesn't — it writes in place. The daemon already handles both patterns correctly.\n\n### 4.2 CRDT Tombstone Growth — Not Relevant Here\nInvestigated whether y-crdt's tombstone accumulation could cause garbled output. It can't — tombstones affect memory/performance, not correctness. The duplication is purely from concurrent large inserts.\n\n### 4.3 Client ID Collisions — Already Fixed\nThe code already uses `randomClientID()` and `doc_load_with_client()` to prevent client ID collisions. This was fixed in commit `1aae181`. Not the current issue.\n\n## 5. Key Discoveries with Evidence\n\n### Discovery 1: The merge base is critically wrong\n\n**Evidence**: `lastSyncBody()` at docs.go:517 returns empty string. The TODO comment says \"track last-sync body hash for better 3-way merge base.\" This was known to be needed but never implemented.\n\nThe code falls back to `creationBody` which is the ORIGINAL note body from creation time. After N edits, this is completely stale.\n\n### Discovery 2: The CRDT is being misused — it's not the tool's fault\n\n**Evidence**: The StackOverflow answer about Yjs explicitly states: \"you are updating yXmlFragment by overwriting its state completely. Yjs interprets that as deleting all existing text and inserting all new text; if two users do so concurrently, they both insert the complete new text, duplicating it.\"\n\nMaitake's merge code effectively does this when the base is stale — the diff sees the entire document as \"new text\" to insert.\n\n### Discovery 3: The YDoc state IS persisted correctly\n\n**Evidence**: The `fold.go` code correctly loads YDocState from base64-encoded ydoc events. The `engine.go` `updateYDoc` function correctly maintains YDoc state through edits. The YDoc state has the CORRECT history of note-side edits. The problem isn't persistence — it's that the merge code IGNORES the existing YDoc's content and instead creates a fresh base from `creationBody`.\n\n### Discovery 4: The solution is already half-built\n\n**Evidence**: The `mergeViaCRDT` function already loads the existing YDoc state and checks `noteContent == fileContent` (early exit when they match). The infrastructure to diff from the correct base is already there — we just need to use the YDoc's content as the base instead of `creationBody`.\n\n## 6. Contradicting Evidence\n\n### Could the CRDT itself produce duplicates even with a correct base?\n**Answer**: Only if both peers make truly identical large inserts at the same position from the same base, which shouldn't happen in the file-sync scenario (one side is the note, the other is the file — they diverge from the same point, they don't both independently create the same content).\n\n### Could the daemon's engine cache cause stale state?\n**Answer**: The `engineCache` in daemon.go reuses the same engine instance for all syncs within a repo. This means the engine doesn't rebuild its index between syncs. This COULD mean a stale index if notes were modified externally, but for the normal Obsidian-editing flow, the engine is the one processing the changes, so it stays current. Not the primary issue.\n\n### Could frequent saves cause race conditions?\n**Answer**: The debounce (500ms for writes, 200ms tick) prevents rapid-fire syncs. Each sync completes before the next one starts (syncFile is synchronous). Not a race condition.\n\n## 7. Synthesis — The Answer\n\n### What's Wrong\n\nThe `mergeViaCRDT` function uses `creationBody` as the 3-way merge base. After even a single edit, this base is stale. The `lastSyncBody()` function was intended to provide the correct base but returns empty string (TODO).\n\nWhen the base is stale, the diffs between base and current content are huge, causing both CRDT peers to insert near-identical large blocks, which the CRDT correctly preserves — resulting in duplication.\n\n### The Correct Design\n\n**Option A: Fix the merge base (Minimum viable fix — RECOMMENDED)**\n\nTrack the \"last sync snapshot\" — the body content at the time of the last successful SyncDocs. This becomes the 3-way merge base.\n\nImplementation:\n1. After each successful merge in SyncDocs, emit a `sync-snapshot` event containing a hash of the synced body\n2. `lastSyncBody()` reads events to find the most recent sync snapshot\n3. Store the actual body text as the sync base (or store a hash and use the note's body history to find the matching version)\n4. On merge, use this as the base instead of `creationBody`\n\nBetter yet: **use the YDoc's own content as the base**. The YDoc already knows what the note-side content is (via `noteDoc.Content()`). The file was last written FROM the YDoc's content. So the correct base for the file-side diff is NOT `creationBody` but **the content that was last written to the file** — which is the YDoc's content at the time of last sync.\n\nConcretely, the fix is:\n```\n// Instead of:\nbase := creationBody\nif base == \"\" {\n    base = noteContent\n}\n\n// Do:\nbase := noteContent  // The file was last synced FROM the note content\n// Actually, the base should be what was last written to disk.\n// That equals the note's body at the time of last sync.\n```\n\nWait — this needs more thought. The note content may have changed SINCE the last sync (e.g., an agent edited the note body between syncs). We need the note's body **at the time of last file write**.\n\nThe simplest correct approach:\n\n**Store a \"last-synced body\" alongside the YDoc state.** Each time SyncDocs writes to disk or updates the note, record the body that both sides agreed on. This becomes the merge base for the next sync.\n\nImplementation:\n1. Add a `sync-base` event (kind=event, field=sync-base, body=\u003cthe agreed body or its hash\u003e)\n2. In `State`, add a `LastSyncBody` field populated during fold\n3. In `mergeViaCRDT`, use `state.LastSyncBody` as the base instead of `creationBody`\n4. When merge completes, emit the sync-base event\n\n**Option B: Drop CRDT, use simple 3-way text merge**\n\nSince maitake's file sync is NOT live collaborative editing (it's periodic batch sync), a CRDT is overkill. A traditional 3-way text merge (like `git merge-file`) would work:\n\n1. Track `lastSyncBody` as in Option A\n2. Use a standard 3-way diff/merge algorithm:\n   - base = lastSyncBody\n   - ours = noteContent\n   - theirs = fileContent\n   - merged = 3-way merge\n3. If conflicts, either: mark them (\u003c\u003c\u003c\u003c ====), or prefer one side\n\nAdvantages: Simpler, no WASM dependency, well-understood algorithm, smaller binary.\nDisadvantages: Can't handle true concurrent character-level edits as well as CRDT. Produces conflict markers instead of automatic merge.\n\n**Option C: Treat CRDT as the single source of truth**\n\nInstead of 3-way merge, make the flow unidirectional per sync cycle:\n1. Note-side edits go INTO the YDoc via diff+apply (already works: `updateYDoc`)\n2. File-side edits: diff the file against `YDoc.Content()` (not creationBody), apply ops to YDoc\n3. Write `YDoc.Content()` back to both note body and file\n\nThis is essentially Option A simplified: the YDoc IS the merge base. The file was last written from YDoc.Content(). The note body was last set from YDoc.Content(). Any divergence since then is the delta to apply.\n\n**RECOMMENDATION: Option C is the best approach.**\n\nIt's the simplest correct design:\n- The YDoc content IS the last-sync base (because every sync writes YDoc.Content() to both note and file)\n- File-side diff: `diff(ydocContent, fileContent)` → apply ops to YDoc\n- Note-side diff: `diff(ydocContent, noteContent)` → apply ops to YDoc\n- After both: `merged = YDoc.Content()`\n- Write merged to note body and file\n\nKey insight: **you don't need to store a separate sync-base**. The YDoc's content AT LOAD TIME is the base, because the last sync set both file and note to that content.\n\nThe bug is essentially that the code creates a FRESH YDoc from `creationBody` instead of using the EXISTING YDoc's content as the merge base.\n\n### The Fix (Pseudocode)\n\n```go\nfunc mergeViaCRDT(state *State, fileContent string, creationBody string) mergeResult {\n    if state.YDocState != nil {\n        noteDoc, err := crdt.Load(state.YDocState)\n        if err == nil {\n            defer noteDoc.Close()\n            ydocContent, _ := noteDoc.Content()\n            \n            // If file matches YDoc, nothing to merge\n            if ydocContent == fileContent {\n                return mergeResult{Body: state.Body, YDocState: state.YDocState}\n            }\n            \n            // File has changed. Apply file diff to the YDoc.\n            // Base = ydocContent (what was last written to file)\n            fileOps := crdt.Diff(ydocContent, fileContent)\n            crdt.ApplyOps(noteDoc, fileOps)\n            \n            // If note body also diverged from YDoc (agent edited note between syncs),\n            // we need a separate peer for note-side edits too\n            if ydocContent != state.Body {\n                // Create a separate peer for note-side changes\n                baseState, _ := noteDoc.Save()  // wait, this already has file changes...\n                // Actually: we need to branch BEFORE applying file ops.\n                // Load YDoc fresh, branch into two peers, merge.\n            }\n            \n            merged, _ := noteDoc.Content()\n            newState, _ := noteDoc.Save()\n            return mergeResult{Body: merged, YDocState: newState}\n        }\n    }\n    // fallback: file wins, init YDoc\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nActually, for the common case (only file changed, or only note changed), this simplifies to:\n\n```go\nfunc mergeViaCRDT(state *State, fileContent string, creationBody string) mergeResult {\n    if state.YDocState != nil {\n        noteDoc, err := crdt.Load(state.YDocState)\n        if err == nil {\n            ydocContent, _ := noteDoc.Content()\n            \n            if ydocContent == fileContent {\n                // File hasn't changed since last sync\n                noteDoc.Close()\n                return mergeResult{Body: state.Body, YDocState: state.YDocState}\n            }\n            \n            // Both may have changed. Use YDoc content as the base.\n            // For the COMMON CASE: only file changed (ydocContent == state.Body)\n            if ydocContent == state.Body {\n                // Only file changed. Apply file diff directly to YDoc.\n                fileOps := crdt.Diff(ydocContent, fileContent)\n                crdt.ApplyOps(noteDoc, fileOps)\n                merged, _ := noteDoc.Content()\n                newState, _ := noteDoc.Save()\n                noteDoc.Close()\n                return mergeResult{Body: merged, YDocState: newState}\n            }\n            \n            // BOTH changed. True 3-way merge needed.\n            // Base = ydocContent (stale YDoc = last sync point)\n            // Wait — ydocContent should EQUAL the note body at last sync\n            // unless updateYDoc failed or wasn't called.\n            \n            // Use YDoc as base. Create file peer from same base.\n            baseState, _ := noteDoc.Save()\n            noteDoc.Close()\n            \n            // Note peer: reload YDoc, it already has note-side edits\n            // Actually the YDoc should ALREADY have note edits (updateYDoc maintains it)\n            // So YDoc content should == state.Body\n            // If ydocContent != state.Body, the YDoc is stale (updateYDoc wasn't called)\n            \n            // Safest: create file peer from YDoc base, apply file diff\n            filePeer, _ := crdt.Load(baseState)\n            defer filePeer.Close()\n            fileOps := crdt.Diff(ydocContent, fileContent)\n            crdt.ApplyOps(filePeer, fileOps)\n            \n            // Note peer: create from same base, apply note diff\n            notePeer, _ := crdt.Load(baseState)\n            defer notePeer.Close()\n            noteOps := crdt.Diff(ydocContent, state.Body)\n            crdt.ApplyOps(notePeer, noteOps)\n            \n            // Merge\n            filePeerState, _ := filePeer.Save()\n            notePeer.Apply(filePeerState)\n            merged, _ := notePeer.Content()\n            newState, _ := notePeer.Save()\n            return mergeResult{Body: merged, YDocState: newState}\n        }\n    }\n    // fallback\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe critical change is: **diff from `ydocContent` (the YDoc's current text), NOT from `creationBody`**.\n\n## 8. Confidence \u0026 Caveats\n\n**Confidence: 9/10** that the stale merge base is the root cause of the duplication bug.\n\n**Caveats:**\n1. I haven't verified that `updateYDoc` is reliably called on every note body change. If some code paths update the note body without updating the YDoc, then YDoc content and note body will diverge, and this fix would still have issues. Need to audit all body-update paths.\n2. The first sync after a note is created (before any YDoc state exists) still needs the fallback path. The current fallback (file wins, init YDoc from file content) is correct.\n3. When `ydocContent != state.Body` (YDoc out of sync with note body), the merge base is ambiguous. The fix should handle this gracefully — probably by treating YDoc content as the base and applying both diffs.\n\n## 9. Divergent Possibilities\n\n### Alternative: The YDoc state could be corrupted\nIf `updateYDoc` has a bug that silently corrupts the YDoc state, then `crdt.Load()` might succeed but return garbage content. This would make `ydocContent` wrong and all diffs would be wrong. I didn't find evidence of this, but it's worth testing with a round-trip assertion in the merge function.\n\n### Alternative: The diff algorithm could produce incorrect ops for large documents\nIf `Diff()` produces ops that are correct for apply-in-sequence but have cumulative position errors, the resulting YDoc content could be garbled. The existing tests cover small documents but not large (~2700 word) documents. Worth adding a large-document diff round-trip test.\n\n### Alternative: Multiple syncs could amplify a small error\nIf a merge produces a slightly garbled result, the next sync would use THAT as the base, and the error could compound. This snowball effect could explain the 40x duplication even from a small initial divergence.\n\n## 10. Concrete Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests for Merge Logic (pkg/notes/)\n\n1. **TestMergeViaCRDT_StaleBase_NoDuplication**: Create a note, edit body 10 times to make creationBody stale. Edit file with a small change. Verify merge doesn't duplicate content.\n\n2. **TestMergeViaCRDT_OnlyFileChanged**: Note hasn't changed since last sync, file has one added line. Merge should produce note+file content with the added line.\n\n3. **TestMergeViaCRDT_OnlyNoteChanged**: File hasn't changed, note body updated by agent. Merge should propagate note change to file.\n\n4. **TestMergeViaCRDT_BothChanged_NoConflict**: Note adds paragraph at end, file adds paragraph at beginning. Merge should have both.\n\n5. **TestMergeViaCRDT_BothChanged_Conflict**: Both sides edit the same line differently. Verify no duplication, one side wins or both preserved cleanly.\n\n6. **TestMergeViaCRDT_LargeDocument**: 2700-word document, small edit on both sides. Verify merged output is ~2700 words (not 5400+).\n\n### Integration Tests Simulating Obsidian (test/)\n\n7. **TestDocs_ObsidianRapidSaves**: Create doc, write file 20 times with small incremental changes (simulating Obsidian auto-save on each keystroke batch), running SyncDocs between some saves. Verify no duplication.\n\n8. **TestDocs_ObsidianFullRewrite**: Create doc, replace entire file content (simulating paste-replace in Obsidian). Verify merge handles full-file replacement correctly.\n\n9. **TestDocs_ObsidianEditWhileAgentEdits**: Start doc, Obsidian adds lines, agent changes title (triggers body update), sync. Verify both changes present, no duplication.\n\n### Adversarial Tests\n\n10. **TestDocs_20SyncsAccumulate_NoDuplication**: Run 20 sync cycles with alternating small edits from file and note sides. Verify document stays reasonable size.\n\n11. **TestDocs_BrokenYDocState_Fallback**: Corrupt the YDoc state (random bytes). Verify merge falls back to file-wins without crash.\n\n12. **TestDocs_EmptyCreationBody_MergeWorks**: Note created with empty body, then file populated. Verify merge works.\n\n### Property-Based Tests\n\n13. **Fuzz TestMerge_OutputContainsAllNewContent**: For any (base, noteEdit, fileEdit) triple, verify the merged output contains all NEW content from both sides.\n\n14. **Fuzz TestMerge_OutputSizeBounded**: For any input, verify `len(merged) \u003c= len(noteContent) + len(fileContent) - len(base) + tolerance`. This catches duplication.\n\n## 11. Summary: Do We Need CRDTs?\n\n**Short answer: No, not strictly. But they're already built and work fine if used correctly.**\n\nThe CRDT adds value for:\n- Automatic merge without conflict markers\n- Future live collaboration (if maitake ever supports it)\n- Correct handling of concurrent character-level edits\n\nA simpler 3-way text merge would also work for the file-sync use case, but would:\n- Produce conflict markers for concurrent edits to the same line\n- Require user intervention to resolve conflicts\n- Not support future live collaboration\n\n**Recommendation: Keep the CRDT, fix the merge base.** The CRDT engine (yrs via WASM) is already working correctly. The fix is a ~20 line change in `mergeViaCRDT` to use YDoc content as the base instead of `creationBody`.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:10:18Z","branch":"main"}

